        {
          "reviewTitle": "You look like what you pay for...",
          "reviewText": "I have a very oily T-zone, even when using my Becca mattifying primer. I was using Chanel Lumiere liquid foundation before this (not the one for oily skin, because I bought it in the winter when I was on a medication that gave me dry patches), which I loved, but I ran out and thought I'd give this much cheaper drugstore foundation with rave reviews a try. This foundation does prevent my typical t zone oil slick from developing when I wear it, even without mattifying primer. The coverage is great, especially with a couple of layers--a little of this goes a long way, so I would say that my typical application is thin. Since the bottle has no pump, I dip a clean q-tip into the bottle instead of touching the foundation and bottle with my fingers. I know that a lot of people hate foundations without a pump, but I like the fact that I can get EVERYTHING out. It kills me that I couldn't get to all of the makeup in my $60 bottle of Chanel foundation. That being said, this foundation feels SO thick on my skin. Maybe I'm just spoiled from using such a high quality liquid foundation before this, but I feel like my face is suffocating when I wear it. It feels like I'm covered in petroleum or something. I wore some just under my eyes, under my powdered mineral foundation yesterday, and when I tried to blend my eyeliner after this had dried, I realized how bad the consistency was...it was just sticky and thick. I guess the plus side to that is you definitely don't have to worry about transferring. It looks so unnatural to me. When I wear it my skin tone is even, blemishes and dark circles covered, but at a price!! My skin looks...weird. Older? I don't know. Just off in a bad way. I actually felt self conscious when I went out wearing this. Speaking of unnatural, the chemical smell of this...the chemicals IN this...I couldn't get over it like I thought I could. I used to be a nut about chemicals in my makeup and body care products....apparently some of that stuck, because I worry about my health when I put this on. My skin tone is hard to match because I'm biracial, so I was impressed that their golden beige worked well for me-- but it became too pale after I went to the pool one day. After that, this stuff really wasn't working for me. I've gone back to using Mineral Fusion loose mineral foundation (warm 2...you can buy this brand at Whole Foods or on Amazon!) instead of liquids in general. My skin looks flawless and natural while I still get full coverage and perfect color match. So Revlon Colorstay for oily/combo skin gets more like 2.5 stars despite my bad feelings for it because of how well it holds back oil, redness coverage, color range, low price....I gave this 3 instead of 2 stars because I was very impressed with the oil control and rarely find anything for oily skin that actually works. I'd rather apply a mattifying primer and pay more for a higher quality foundation than wear this, though.",
